# Git Commands Best Practices

## Context
- **MUST READ THIS RULE** before using any Git commands in terminal operations
- When analysing Git repository state
- When running Git commands that might trigger a pager
- When automating Git operations

## Requirements
- Use `--no-pager` flag with Git commands that might trigger a pager
- Ensure direct output without user intervention
- Apply to log, diff, show, and other commands that display content

## Examples

<example>
# Good: Using --no-pager flag
git --no-pager log --oneline -10
git --no-pager diff --stat main..HEAD
git --no-pager show --stat HEAD
git --no-pager diff --name-only main..HEAD
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Bad: Commands that may trigger pager
git log --oneline -10
git diff --stat main..HEAD
git show --stat HEAD
</example>

## Critical Rules
- ALWAYS use `--no-pager` with log, diff, show, and similar commands
- NEVER assume Git commands will output directly without pager
